<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0828-B"><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Since entering federal prison in October, Martha Stewart has tried her hand at ceramics, learned to crochet and become an expert on vending-machine snacks.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="7" sums="14,16,23,36,44,5,55"><scu uid="5" label="She crocheted" weight="3"/><scu uid="6" label="She did ceramics" weight="3"/><scu uid="4" label="She became an expert on vending-machine snacks" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Stewart and her former stockbroker, Peter Bacanovic, were convicted in March of lying about why Stewart unloaded shares of ImClone Systems Inc. stock in 2001, just before the price plunged.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>In an interview last month with CNN's Larry King, her daughter, Alexis Stewart, acknowledged that her mother loves the holidays and that spending them in prison would be very hard.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>Stewart herself addressed the restrictions in a letter posted on marthatalks.com.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Not for her the recipes touted on her company's Web site as meals that will &quot;make you wish your plate were bigger.&quot;</line><line>The Singing Angels, a gospel choir made up of Alderson inmates, will perform at the Presbyterian church.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>&quot;The criminal justice system is not about cleansing one's soul,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Roach also recounted some of Stewart's prison activities.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="10,32,40,6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>Don Fernandez writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Roach said Stewart will plant a garden in an old estate she has been renovating in Bedford.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>After undergoing chemotherapy in Tacoma, Washington, Kathy Herrmann flew across the United States to see Martha Stewart as she left a federal prison in West Virginia early Friday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="12,14,23,25,29,44,55"/></line><line>The former prison minister is used to high-profile inmates at the minimum-security prison, but &quot;it wasn't as exciting as&quot; Stewart's stay and departure.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Stewart said her &quot;daily interactions with the staff and fellow inmates here at Alderson are marked by fair treatment and mutual respect.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>&quot;I have had time to think, time to write, time to exercise, time to not eat the bad food, and time to walk and contemplate the future,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>&quot;The prison episode right from the beginning has been successfully spun.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>(Stewart relinquished the title amid the controversy, and law prohibits her from regaining control of the company.)</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>&quot;We use prison too much and often for the wrong things,&quot; Sarat said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Not this year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>Some came to experience the moment.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Stewart foraged for wild greens such as dandelion on prison property &quot;to augment the limited fresh vegetable offerings in the diet there,&quot; helped decorate the chapel for a memorial service and made microwave meals &quot;with whatever very basic ingredients the commissary had for sale.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>After her house-arrest term expires, Stewart will be on probation for two more years.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>We don't have a lot going on, and things are mighty slow,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>It's a great thing.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>&quot;They are always an opportunity to celebrate family, friends and religious traditions that mean so much to many of us,&quot; she said then.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>But the company's share price rose steadily during the five months Stewart was in prison, closing on Thursday at $33.95, up from a low of $8.25 in May.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>&quot;It would be great for the brand and great for Martha.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>The television show is scheduled to air after the five months of house arrest end.</line><line>The appeals court is expected to hear the case early in 2005.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Newsweek noted her post-conviction fame in its cover this week headlined: &quot;Martha's Last Laugh: After Prison, She's Thinner, Wealthier and Ready for Prime Time.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>&quot;They utilize the most cost-effective purchase options,&quot; said spokeswoman Dawn Zobel, who explained that prison officials regularly scan the Internet to find the least expensive foodstuffs.</line><line>The domestic diva's family shouldn't count on eating with Stewart, however.</line><line>The orders come in practically every day, from across the country -- more than 800 so far.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>Stewart is reportedly in fighting shape, having lost 20 pounds in prison while impressing the locals with her down-to-earth attitude.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="1" label="She lost 20 pounds" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>But William Parr, 66, of Amherst, Virginia, said Stewart will rebound because she has the &quot;Midas touch.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>The company has been working with reality TV pioneer Mark Burnett, and shares of the media company have soared since Stewart reported to prison _ although they have fallen back somewhat in recent weeks.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>But Stewart has used prison to soften her image -- to make her, in the public eye, a more sympathetic person than the perfectionist entertainer and executive she was seen to be before her sentence.</line><line>&quot;I have to believe that confronted with the same circumstances she would act differently,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>&quot;This country is all about second chances,&quot; Burnett said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>People go to prison and serve their time; once they have done so, they're through, Becker said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>No holiday centerpieces.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>&quot;I came down just because it's history.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>Stewart went to jail with her head held high even as friends, advertisers and investors deserted her seemingly sinking name-brand ship: She returns to the outside world neither bowed nor broken, but ready to reclaim her spot at the top of, well, almost everything.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>&quot;This year, we usher in spring with an extra measure of gratitude, because the month of March not only marks the vernal equinox on the twentieth and the real start of our Northeast growing season, but also Martha's homecoming,&quot; Margaret Roach, editor in chief of Martha Stewart Living, wrote in the magazine's March edition.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Her March 6 release also creates a one-of-a-kind marketing opportunity for her company, one that is not lost on Mark Burnett, the &quot;Survivor&quot; producer who is planning a daily live-audience program featuring Stewart for NBC this fall.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>She chose to begin serving her time even as her appeal wends its way through the legal system.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>Huff was talking to a friend earlier in the evening when she decided to make the 64-mile (100-kilometer) trip to Alderson.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>In December, the town will host its annual Christmas celebration, throwing open the doors to decorated old mansions for tours.</line><line>The turkey, mashed potatoes, gravy, dressing and pumpkin pie will be prepared by inmates in the camp kitchen.</line><line>Stewart has always said she loves the holidays, which helped create her media empire as millions of women tried out her seasonal recipes and decorating tips in hopes of capturing the country elegance of a Martha celebration.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="3"/></line><line>The turkey was a native of Mathias, W.Va.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>But when she decided to go to jail, now she looks more contrite,&quot; Huff said.</line><line>I've followed her for the last 20 years,&quot; said Parr, who drove about 100 miles (160 kilometers) to see Stewart.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>Nonetheless, Stewart is nothing if not resilient.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>Conceivably, her success could subtly undermine the deterrent effect of a prison sentence, but that is neither here nor there, said David Becker, a former general counsel at the Securities and Exchange Commission who is now in private practice in Washington.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>&quot;That's what makes it the greatest country in the world.&quot;</line><line>And when Stewart completes her sentence six weeks from now, colleagues at her company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, anticipate an even bigger payoff.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="21,22,32,42"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Stewart's time in jail officially ends Sunday, but the federal prisons bureau can release prisoners on a Friday if their sentences end over the weekend, said US prisons spokeswoman Carla Wilson.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="33,40"/></line><line>&quot;I can tell you she is, indeed, ready to get planting, having ordered her seeds and made extensive to-do lists, just as she would have done in any winter,&quot; the editor wrote.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>&quot;It achieved everything the government wanted it not to achieve,&quot; said Nina Marino, a defense lawyer in Beverly Hills, Calif.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>&quot;We have a lot of bills to pay.</line><line>The holiday is one of a sequence she will miss while on the inside, including Halloween, Christmas and New Year's.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>&quot;If she gets behind prison reform, then she becomes Saint Martha,&quot; said Hayes Roth, a brand consultant with Landor Associates in New York.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>If nothing else, he suggested, Stewart has probably learned not to lie to federal investigators.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>Martha Stewart, the billionaire entrepreneur who was convicted a year ago of lying to federal investigators, left prison early Friday in Alderson, W.Va., after serving a five-month sentence.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="13" sums="10,11,13,14,22,23,25,29,41,43,44,49,55"><scu uid="22" label="Her sentence lasted 5 months" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>Punishing wrongdoing, the theory goes, has two primary goals: to penalize the wrongdoer and to deter potential wrongdoers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>What a difference a few months in prison can make.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>According to Stewart's aides, the head of the empire is very optimistic about her future.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>America's favorite domestic convict may have literally become a captive audience, but don't break out the glue stick and glitter for a greeting.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>There will be no sweet potato spoon bread this year for Martha Stewart.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="32,51,57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>Then, too, the negative impact of Stewart's conviction was mitigated by the nature of the crime.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>Stewart, 63, must still serve five months in home detention at her estate in Bedford, N.Y., to complete her sentence for lying about the timing of a 2001 sale of shares in ImClone Systems.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Whether American consumers view her as a more sympathetic person, or are just curious what she'll be like after prison, doesn't seem to matter to marketing experts, some of whom think she will be able to take advantage of the renewed interest either way.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>Last year, Herrmann and others attended Stewart's trial in federal court in Manhattan.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>She will be allowed, however, to be filmed at her estate.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Stewart, who is roughly halfway through a five-month sentence for lying about a stock sale, urged fans to think about the women she has met in prison who are &quot;devoid of care, devoid of love, devoid of family.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>&quot;From the government's perspective, the objective of incarceration is to punish someone, and I think that Martha Stewart has, ingeniously, instead of being punished turned it to her advantage.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>While they would not disclose specific figures, executives at Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia say licensing fees for the daytime show &quot;are trending significantly higher&quot; than those for Stewart's original show, even at its peak.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>The better question: Who in their right mind is sending Martha Stewart money?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Though the prison has hosted famous inmates before, none seem to have elicited quite as much interest as Stewart, who has brought with her a seemingly endless stream of reporters and tourists to shop in the stores and eat in the town's two restaurants.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>The company's shares hit a low of $10.86 that day, slipping even further the following week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>She added, &quot;Someday, I hope to have the chance to talk more about all that has happened, the extraordinary people I have met here and all that I have learned.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>Instead, if you are so inclined, please make a donation to the American Cancer Society, a charitable organization that means a lot to me,&quot; she wrote.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Privacy rules prohibit Zobel from disclosing whether Stewart, 63, will be helping to prepare the feast, and her spokespeople aren't talking.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>In April's issue of Martha Stewart Living, Stewart's column will resume; magazine readers were prepped for the return by editor Margaret Roach, who wrote in March about Martha's indomitable spirit during her incarceration.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="22,43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Martha Stewart, in a Christmas message posted on her personal Web site, called for sentencing reform and took a swipe at the &quot;bad food&quot; in prison.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="6" sums="11,19,20,29,40,57"><scu uid="17" label="Stewart became a prison reform advocate " weight="3"/><scu uid="3" label="She disliked prison food" weight="2"/><scu uid="33" label="She kept in touch through her web site" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Zobel said the decision to limit the meal to inmates was a &quot;procedural change&quot; announced in August by the camp's new warden and was driven partly by budgetary concerns.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>E-mail: dfernandezajc.com</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>There are still some challenges, of course, the largest of which is five more months of incarceration, albeit at her 153-acre estate in Bedford, N.Y. Stewart's movements will be monitored by an ankle bracelet, she'll have regular appointments with a court officer, and while she's allowed 48 hours of work time each week outside the house, her movements must be accounted for.</line><line>The specter of a civil suit (separate and different from the criminal for which she went to prison) filed by the SEC hovers, though it's been reported that negotiations are under way for a settlement that would allow Stewart to reclaim her CEO status in five years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>Stewart will star in two television series and plans to resume writing her monthly column for Martha Stewart Living magazine and working at her office, one of the few places where she can go other than her 153-acre estate.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>Herrmann and several friends stood at the Greenbrier Valley airport in minus 9 Celsius (16 Farenheit) weather holding a Martha Stewart-brand floral print sheet with signatures from Seattle area fans.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,57"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>She will also star in a show focusing on the same subjects that she built into a multi-million dollar lifestyle empire -- cooking, entertaining, decorating and home renovating.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Instead, Stewart's relatives could attend some of the seasonal events that kick off this week in Alderson, a town of 1,100 that has been home to the nation's oldest federal prison for women since it opened in 1927.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="3"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>Such cruelty.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0135"><line>Newsweek said it did not intend to fool readers in any way and regretted if the photo illustration left any misimpression.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>&quot;And like anything else we use too much, and for the wrong things, it loses its currency.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Stewart's reputation has made a massive public rebound during her time in Alderson, despite the conviction for lying about a dodgy stock sale.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="31" label="She became a more sympathetic character" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>She was released from prison about 12:30 a.m., according to a statement at the prison, the road crowded with journalists and fans.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Both are appealing.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>She also launched a yoga class that she taught for 10 inmates, spent time crocheting and used old molds to create a nativity scene for her mother.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>&quot;I think jail has been great for her.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>But Stewart has won a contract to host a spin-off of tycoon Donald Trump's successful television reality show &quot;The Apprentice.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Stewart, who built a billion-dollar empire in homemaking, reported that her job at the federal prison camp in Alderson, West Virginia, has been cleaning, including sweeping, vacuuming and raking leaves.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="10,5"><scu uid="9" label="Martha's prison job was cleaning" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Thanksgiving Day comes on Day 48 of Stewart's five-month stay at the sprawling minimum-security campus on the Greenbrier River.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>To many, that just does not seem terribly heinous.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>&quot;I have been told that some of these letters have included gifts and money.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>For her, &quot;the last five months in Alderson, West Virginia, has been life altering and life affirming,&quot; Stewart gushed in a statement on her Web site on Friday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>This weekend, several galleries and stores on Railroad Avenue will host their annual open houses.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>Was the conviction of Martha Stewart for lying to federal investigators worth the effort?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="0,23,29,49,51"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>She has a new boss in CEO Susan Lyne, who's used to working for high-profile personalities (Rupert Murdoch, Michael Eisner) and has been a calm voice of reasoned support during the hoopla.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Instead, officials report that Stewart -- and her 1,050 fellow inmates at West Virginia's Alderson Federal Prison Camp, where she is serving time for lying about a stock sale -- can expect a more traditional Thanksgiving meal.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="11,13,35,37,49,51,6"><scu uid="25" label="She spent Thanksgiving in prison" weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>Nobody is saying whether the jail birds will be frozen, or fresh, as the nation's homemaker-in-chief might prefer.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>Prison, it seems, was a good thing.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>&quot;When she went in, I thought she was mean.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="47"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>&quot;We're in rural West Virginia.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>No cakes (especially ones with files baked inside).</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Although the prison generally allows only weekend visits, Stewart's family can take advantage of special hours Thursday, from 8 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. Inmates, who all are required to hold a prison job, get the day off, with the exception of those who work in the powerhouse and, of course, the kitchen.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="29" label="Family visits normally were limited to weekends" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Among the things the town is thankful for this year is Stewart, whom they have adopted since she slipped through the gates of the prison down the road before dawn Oct.8.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>So even if Stewart emerged from the Big House a hotter commodity than when she went in, justice could still have been served, Becker said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>She began serving her sentence in October.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>While Martha Stewart may receive letters from fans and well-wishers while serving her sentence at Federal Prison Camp Alderson in West Virginia -- affectionately known as Camp Cupcake -- any crafts or other homemade concoctions are strictly forbidden.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="6" sums="10,3,35,37,43,6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>This weekend marks the end of Stewart's five-month prison sentence, a term she chose to get over with by eschewing the option of milking the appeals process.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>&quot;Stewart is very successful at spin,&quot; said Austin Sarat, a professor of jurisprudence and political science at Amherst College.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Some investors and analysts believe the shares are now over-priced and could fall back to earth soon after the interest in Stewart's post-prison status fades.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>But she said a &quot;whole bunch of her family&quot; would travel to Alderson to celebrate Thanksgiving.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>E-mail: ldempsey@DaytonDailyNews.com</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>The cross-country trip was not their first to support the homemaking queen.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>The sales, she said, will make this a nice Thanksgiving indeed for her family.</line><line>Stewart stepped down as company chairman and chief executive after her indictment last year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>Her company's stock, which represents the bulk of her fortune, crumbled amid the scandal, and she had to settle for the title of founder.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>A prison spokeswoman could promise only that they will be as cheap as possible.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Scores of employees were laid off, and merchandise sales, mainly through Kmart, declined.</line><line>If she gets back to running the basics of the business and has this added patina, if you will, of having suffered and moved ahead in her life -- well, Americans love that.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>&quot;The camp is like an old-fashioned college campus -- without the freedom, of course.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>That ended with Stewart begin convicted on charges of lying about a 2001 stock sale.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0135"><line>Martha Stewart, who is about to get out of prison, seems to have undergone a makeover on the cover of the latest Newsweek.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="14,25,32,36,44"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>One of the tasks ahead of Stewart is to try and spin the goodwill she gained in prison into profits for her Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia Inc. Despite high stock prices, the company has posted a loss last year.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="16,21,36,37,42,6"><scu uid="31" label="She became a more sympathetic character" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>(Optional Add End)</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>But the newsweekly is also in trouble for using the head of Stewart on the body of a model for the cover picture.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0135"><line>Newsweek editors said there was nothing wrong with the &quot;photo illustration,&quot; given that it's well known Stewart hasn't done any fashion spreads from prison in West Virginia.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>The prison term ended at 12:30 a.m. (0530GMT) Friday when she was released.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>Once the chairman and chief executive of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, she had to give up both titles after she was indicted in 2003.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>Not everyone in the crowd was a fan.</line><line>&quot;I'm tired but it meant enough for me to come out here anyway,&quot; Herrmann said, who had her chemotherapy treatment on Wednesday.</line><line>&quot;I love this lady.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>&quot;The tales were always surprising,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>&quot;She's been a blessing to the prison and a blessing to the girls there,&quot; said Hattie Hopkins.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>No cornbread sourdough stuffing, no cranberry pear chutney.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>Of course, Stewart is a most unusual ex-con; few have her public relations savvy or resources.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>&quot;She has definitely got her act together on the home front.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>Laura Dempsey writes for the Dayton Daily News.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>US lifestyle guru Martha Stewart is expected to leave jail on Friday after a five-month sentence for a stock scandal that reinvigorated her career rather than dooming it.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="21,33,40,51"><scu uid="22" label="Her sentence lasted 5 months" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Since Stewart's conviction, her company's share price has nearly tripled, increasing her personal stake to an estimated $827 million from $318 million.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>When she announced in September that she would enter prison soon, Stewart noted specifically how &quot;very sad&quot; she would be to miss the holidays this year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>Even homemade cards are iffy as glitter, ribbons, glue and stickers are no-nos.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Still, the shares are way up from their lows of about $8.50 just before her sentencing last July.</line><line>Doing time -- or what her friends call &quot;the intermission&quot; -- has breathed new life into the company's shares.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Stewart is due to be released in early March from prison, then must spend five months confined to her home in Bedford.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Patti Grafton at the Wolf Creek Gallery will serve mulled cider.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>She suggested Americans should push for reforms in federal sentencing guidelines for nonviolent first-time offenders and particularly for drug offenders, who she said would be better served by rehabilitation than prison.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="17" label="Stewart became a prison reform advocate " weight="3"/><scu uid="19" label="She advocated sentencing reform for drug and first-time offenders" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>She has also gotten a lot wealthier.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Earlier this month, her company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, announced Stewart would host a daytime talk show with a live studio audience beginning this fall.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="36" label=" Stewart was to host a daytime talk show " weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>Please know that while these gestures of friendship and support are deeply appreciated, any such items must be returned to the sender by prison officials.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>Shares in Stewart's company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia Inc. hit a 52-week high last week, though the company announced a record loss of $60 million in 2004, nearly 10 times the loss it suffered in 2003.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="16,19,22,41,48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Revenue plunged to $127.2 million through last September compared with $175 million a year earlier, and the company is expected to post a loss for 2004.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0135"><line>Stewart's face was placed on someone else's body for the cover story &quot;Martha's Last Laugh,&quot; making the 63-year-old look terrific after five months behind bars.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Prison officials declined even to specify whether the turkeys will come from a local farm, like the 44-pound bird pardoned last week at the White House by President Bush.</line><line>In a Thanksgiving message posted yesterday on www.marthatalks.com -- not marthastewart.com, official Web site of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia Inc. -- she told fans that she is &quot;safe, fit and healthy,&quot; though she acknowledged that &quot;the loss of freedom and the lack of privacy are extremely difficult.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>She was never criminally charged with insider trading, but rather with lying to investigators looking into a stock sale in December 2001.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>I'm definitely not a fan,&quot; said Lisa Huff of Bluefield, Virginia.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>She must wear a monitoring bracelet and cannot work away from home for more than 48 hours a week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>For Martha Stewart, a felony conviction is not such a good thing.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="11,32,51"/></line><line>Mark Burnett, impressed by Stewart's moxy, pitched two television shows: One is an &quot;Apprentice&quot; spinoff; the other, a resumption and update of her former daytime how-to program, &quot;Martha Stewart Living Television.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>When Stewart was convicted last March of lying to investigators, the future looked grim for the lifestyle company she created.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>Stewart boarded a private jet for the flight to New York, where she must spend five months of home confinement at her 153-acre (62-hectare) estate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041027.0294"><line>So how are her new digs?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>The stock closed Wednesday at $28.31, down 2.1 percent from the previous day, after the company announced plans to shutter its catalog and online divisions in February.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>Fellow inmates at &quot;Camp Cupcake&quot; (West Virginia's Alderson Federal Prison Camp), have rallied to her side, shielding her from paparazzi while she's scoured the grounds for fresh salad greens and taught yoga.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="35"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0135"><line>&quot;Anybody who knows the story and is familiar with Martha's current situation would know this particular picture&quot; was an illustration and not a photograph, said assistant managing editor Lynn Staley.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Roach even told how Stewart had carried out a yoga pose called &quot;downward-facing dog&quot; in the visitors' room at the prison &quot;from which she seamlessly moved into a headstand.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>&quot;It's all about support.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Shares of the Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia (MSO) empire, which she founded, were up 4.81 percent Thursday, trading at 33.58 dollars in afternoon trading.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>Betty Alderson, who is married to a descendant of the town's founder and owns the 117-year-old Alderson Store, just keeps selling her Martha-themed T-shirts.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>She will still have to serve five months under confinement at her country estate in Bedford, New York.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>She added that she is &quot;very grateful&quot; this Thanksgiving for the support of her friends, family and colleagues, as well has that of her fans who, she wrote, have sent more than 15,000 e-mails.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>But in Stewart's case, it is not clear that either goal was achieved.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>The new papers, like Stewart's previous arguments, argue that prosecutors improperly implied she was accused of insider trading and that a government expert witness on ink analysis lied on the stand.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>Supporters eagerly awaited her release from the Alderson minimum security prison in West Virginia, which inmates call &quot;Camp Cupcake&quot;.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>And that could present a problem for criminal law enforcement.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>In years past, Thanksgiving was the one day of the year when inmates' families were allowed past visiting rooms and into the heart of the camp where, for $1.75, they could share in the feast.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Her life inside the prison -- with its predawn wakeup calls, unappealing food and suffering fellow inmates -- has been sufficiently chronicled so that the 63-year-old Stewart seems more a sympathetic character than a frosty prima donna concerned only about her own agenda.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050304.0341"><line>As part of her sentence, Stewart was ordered to serve five months at the federal women's camp in Alderson.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="18,41,49,5"><scu uid="22" label="Her sentence lasted 5 months" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>The businesswoman was convicted in March last year of lying to federal agents investigating her sale of nearly 4,000 shares in biotechnology company ImClone Systems.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041123.0157"><line>It's been good to have to that extra padding there to help us out.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Stewart site: http://www.marthatalks.com</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050303.0597"><line>A large media group was also outside the prison.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041223.0007"><line>Lawyers for Stewart filed new papers Wednesday with the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, urging it to overturn her conviction.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>Her time at the federal minimum-security women's prison was behind her, but her appeal of that sentence has yet to be heard by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0151"><line>Stewart won't be allowed to fraternize with other felons, meaning the friends she made in prison are off limits.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="25,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050119.0247"><line>Her flagship television show, Martha Stewart Living, was placed on hiatus after losing many of its CBS viewers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0049"><line>Some rap musicians have for years burnished their street credibility through weapons possession charges or worse.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0016"><line>From there, she was expected to travel to the Greenbrier Valley Airport, where she was to board a private plane.</line></document></collection>